-27-0984</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Many organizations that are exposed to the risks of severe operational breakdowns, such as commercial airlines, implement incident reporting programmes. Personnel are encouraged to report minor errors and near-misses so that these can be analysed, investigated and learnt from. However, how risks are practically assessed and managed in these incident reporting programmes has received little empirical scrutiny. This research addresses this issue by examining the interpretive practice of flight safety investigators: how they define risk and safety; how they interpret incidents and identify risks; and how they manage and act on risks. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>Adopting a qualitative, ethnographic research approach, based on a range of interviews and participant observation, allows this expert practice to be studied in its natural organisational context. The findings document the challenging nature of investigators? interpretive work and develop a theoretical account of interpretive practice in this setting. Investigators? practical theory of safety, their approach to identifying risks and their means of subsequently acting on these risks are explored in turn through the analytical concepts of resilience, vigilance and participation. Characterising these three aspects of expert practice in this specific setting develops connections between the fields of risk analysis, high-reliability organising and organisational learning.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2006-12-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2006-01-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>32620</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">PTA-026-27-0984</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>5858EC49-4786-4440-8352-1AB0B6DC5F23</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Psychology</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject></gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchTopics><gtr:researchTopic><gtr